******
[2] New Mexico
Date: Wed 17 Sep 2014
Source: The Albuquerque Journal [edited]
http://www.abqjournal.com/463822/abqnewsseeker/fourth-hantavirus-case-confirmed-in-nm.html


A 50-year-old San Juan County man was hospitalized with hantavirus pulmonary syndrome, marking New Mexico's 4th case of the viral illness this year [2014], including 2 that resulted in deaths, health officials said today [17 Sep 2014].

New Mexico Department of Health officials will perform an environmental investigation to determine the source of the infection and reduce risk to others.

Hantavirus[es] is [infections cause] a deadly disease transmitted by infected rodents through urine, droppings, or saliva. The deer mouse is the main reservoir for Sin Nombre virus, the hantavirus strain found in New Mexico.

Early symptoms of [Sin Nombre] hantavirus infection include fever and muscle aches, possibly with chills, headache, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, abdominal pain, and cough, progressing to respiratory distress. Seek prompt medical attention for symptoms.

"The best defense against hantavirus [infection] is to avoid disturbing areas of rodent infestation, including nests and droppings," said Dr Paul Ettestad, the agency's public health veterinarian.

Air out cabins before entering and wet down rodent dropping with a disinfectant. Trap mice until they are gone and clean up trash around your residence. Seal up holes and cracks in residential buildings to prevent mice from getting inside.

Other cases this year [2014] include a fatal case in a 67-year-old San Juan County woman, a fatal case in a 59-year-old McKinley County man, and a case in a 32-year-old San Juan County woman who survived.

[Byline: Olivier Uyttebrouck]

